<paragraph id="78E83371FAC61C06E8964DD8FC97CE60" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="67BE144BCDEF5F803DA0E5854B84156D" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">The patronymic name honors Prof. Farouk El-Baz, the Egyptian space scientist, Boston University, USA in recognition of his distinguished scientific achievements.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="658397812DE030C70E327CFEFCF994FB" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="DC861624BAA3CBCC43528F5A1A8ACE21" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6B250D121AF3B74216E63E9752EE1891" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
The occurrence of hairs and their distribution on the surface of the body are diagnostic characters for the recognition of species in many ant genera, notably used in the taxonomy of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="5C76DCF45B1E7AEC2D7935CD9E19E855" authorityName="Santschi" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Lepisiota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lepisiota" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="361E7691E1D9F618143D927BED07E6EE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Lepisiota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="23B9890D611BE8570B9E894C31E5B4C6" author="Collingwood, CA" journalOrPublisher="Fauna of Saudi Arabia" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" pagination="230 - 302" refId="B19" refString="Collingwood, CA, 1985. Hymenoptera: Fam. Formicidae of Saudi Arabia. Fauna of Saudi Arabia 7: 230 - 302" title="Hymenoptera: Fam. Formicidae of Saudi Arabia." volume="7" year="1985">Collingwood 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="FFAB4FA7A72E8DDFE166B77B8CDFBB74" author="Collingwood, CA" journalOrPublisher="Fauna of Saudi Arabia" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" pagination="300 - 385" refId="B20" refString="Collingwood, CA, Agosti, D, 1996. Formicidae (Insecta: Hymenoptera) of Saudi Arabia (part 2). Fauna of Saudi Arabia 15: 300 - 385" title="Formicidae (Insecta: Hymenoptera) of Saudi Arabia (part 2)." volume="15" year="1996">Collingwood and Agosti 1996</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="85F4C9D2A5FF923ED0065F2DFD9318DD" authorityName="Sharaf &amp; Hita Garcia" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Lepisiota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lepisiota elbazi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elbazi">
<emphasis id="E7C42894BBBF6BE9F30BD0C7FCF1A269" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Lepisiota elbazi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not similar to any of the known Arabian 
<taxonomicName id="CC22E06E275377DD15D323809B26C62D" authorityName="Santschi" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Lepisiota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lepisiota" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="20108CC6C96DEB3190328B034D9C933C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Lepisiota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except the Arabian endemic species 
<taxonomicName id="EB98BFA7C53AD1869A722DE6AAABB5DA" genus="L." lsidName="L. arabica" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis id="32CC51D3B9FEE30086BEC64E42682599" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">L. arabica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Collingwood, 1985) described from the southwestern Asir Mountains, KSA. Both species are bicolored and have a compressed posterior margin of the head when seen in profile, acute and long propodeal spines, stiff and blunt hairs, impressed metanotal groove, characteristically paler first gastral tergite and similar body sculpture. The compressed profile of the posterior margin of the head sets the two species apart from any of the Arabian 
<taxonomicName id="46338FEA54745A6291ABB7A06D140E5F" authorityName="Santschi" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Lepisiota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lepisiota" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E0E3FACAE2A5873E10019CA5C4C87365" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Lepisiota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as those all have a rounded profile to the posterior margin of the head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3EAB90F788177704909E3CC3BB7FFF6F" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
The two species can be separated by the number of body hairs and dimensions. 
<taxonomicName id="B254CEB1EE7592631F3CC8A465295502" authorityName="Sharaf &amp; Hita Garcia" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Lepisiota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lepisiota elbazi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elbazi">
<emphasis id="3FB0A686DD3283C4E2BB5F8387407F22" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Lepisiota elbazi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has fewer hairs on the posterior margin of the head (two pairs), on the mesosoma (two to three pairs on promesonotum), and on the first gastral tergite (one to two pairs). 
<taxonomicName id="530E2E669B7842B38E2456247486EE1B" baseAuthorityName="Collingwood" baseAuthorityYear="1985" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Lepisiota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lepisiota arabica" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis id="929F8F441D06B9A35E54E1D76C0C379A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Lepisiota arabica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has more than seven pairs of hairs on the posterior margin of the head, many pairs scattered on the mesosomal dorsum (six pairs on promesonotum, four pairs on mesonotum, and two pairs on the propodeal dorsum), and several pairs on the first gastral tergite. Additionally, 
<taxonomicName id="2F1196958466D972FC2621880904AF33" genus="L." lsidName="L. elbazi" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" rank="species" species="elbazi">
<emphasis id="2524A1772FA5AA0D88528F744ED38D4C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">L. elbazi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a greater head length (HL 0.82-0.87 vs. HL 0.72-0.77 in 
<taxonomicName id="1CB56CC8D3AECF21C3E874EBF8ACF109" genus="L." lsidName="L. arabica" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis id="007E2B5DDD4B80831C443C455C54B530" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">L. arabica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), longer scapes (SL 1.07-1.15, SI 185-188 vs. SL 0.87-0.89, SI 155-159), and relatively longer head (HL 0.82-0.87 vs. HL 0.73-0.75).
</paragraph>
